<exercise checkit-seed="0005" checkit-slug="AD2" checkit-title="Linear Approximation">
    <statement>
        <p>
Suppose the function <m>p(x)</m> satisfies
<m>p(-1) = -8</m>, <m>p'(-1) = 5</m>,
and <m>p''(x) &gt; 0</m> for <m>x</m>
values nearby <m>-1</m>.
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
Explain and demonstrate
how to find the linearization <m>L(x)</m>
of <m>p(x)</m> at <m>x =-1</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
Explain and demonstrate
how to estimate the value of <m>p(-1.09)</m> using
this linearization.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
Explain why your estimate of
<m>p(-1.09)</m>
is greater than or less than the actual value.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
Sketch a possible graph of <m>p(x)</m> and its linearization <m>L(x)</m> nearby <m>x =-1</m>
to illustrate your findings.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
<m>L(x)=5 \, x - 3</m>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
<m>p(-1.09) \approx -8.45</m>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
The estimate is less than than the actual value.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </answer>
</exercise>
